\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces Cross-paper pipeline. Paper\nonbreakingspace 0 defines on-chain AI agents via four conditions (C1--C4) and validates an eight-category taxonomy on 2,590 addresses. Paper\nonbreakingspace 1 uses the same 23 features for binary agent/human identification on 1,147 provenance-verified addresses (honest GAT AUC 0.832). Paper\nonbreakingspace 3 tests whether LLM-driven Sybils can evade airdrop detectors; 8 AI-specific features from Paper\nonbreakingspace 1 recover AUC 0.987 even after all HasciDB rules are defeated. The feedback arrow represents Paper\nonbreakingspace 3's finding that the LLM-Powered Agent category (F1 = 0.528 in Paper\nonbreakingspace 0) needs the 8 AI features to become distinguishable. Dashed arrows show shared data dependencies.}}{3}{figure.caption.5}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:pipeline}{{1}{3}{Cross-paper pipeline. Paper~0 defines on-chain AI agents via four conditions (C1--C4) and validates an eight-category taxonomy on 2,590 addresses. Paper~1 uses the same 23 features for binary agent/human identification on 1,147 provenance-verified addresses (honest GAT AUC 0.832). Paper~3 tests whether LLM-driven Sybils can evade airdrop detectors; 8 AI-specific features from Paper~1 recover AUC 0.987 even after all HasciDB rules are defeated. The feedback arrow represents Paper~3's finding that the LLM-Powered Agent category (F1 = 0.528 in Paper~0) needs the 8 AI features to become distinguishable. Dashed arrows show shared data dependencies}{figure.caption.5}{}}
